# Scaling

When designing a system’s architecture, understanding and planning for scalability is crucial. Particularly because Helios handles unbounded event streams, as data volumes grow and user demands increase, the ability to efficiently handle larger workloads becomes paramount.

## Vertical vs Horizontal Scaling ClickHouse

When addressing scalability, two primary approaches are commonly considered: vertical scaling and horizontal scaling. Vertical scaling, often referred to as "scaling up," involves increasing the resources (such as CPU, RAM, or storage) of existing servers. This method is typically simpler to implement but has upper limits based on hardware constraints. Horizontal scaling, or "scaling out," involves adding more servers to distribute the load. While potentially more complex to manage, this approach often offers greater flexibility and theoretical scalability limits.

![][image1]

As noted previously in the “Deploying ClickHouse” section, we decided to follow ClickHouses’ recommendation and host the ClickHouse database on one EC2 instance.

The chosen architecture presents several important trade-offs. By deploying everything on a single EC2 instance, we significantly reduce deployment complexity, avoiding the intricacies of managing multiple ClickHouse shards.

Per ClickHouse, “A shard is a subset of data. ClickHouse always has at least one shard for your data, so if you do not split the data across multiple servers, your data will be stored in one shard.”

However, this approach limits scalability options, primarily restricting us to vertical scaling and making horizontal scaling more challenging. Additionally, the single-instance setup introduces a potential single point of failure. We mitigate this with daily backups of the database within an S3 bucket and persistent storage within AWS EBS. In the event of an EC2 instance failure, recovery would require spinning up a new instance and restoring data from the EBS volume, which will ensure that data is not lost but could lead to temporary service interruption.

While this design follows best practices for ClickHouse database hosting, simplifies management, and reduces costs, it does so at the potential expense of more robust scalability and high availability options that a distributed setup might offer.

## How Much Load Can Our Single Node Handle?

Load testing can play a vital role in understanding the limits an architecture can handle. By simulating real-world usage scenarios, load testing helps identify performance bottlenecks, system limitations, and areas for optimization before they become critical issues in production environments.

ClickHouse conducted open-source benchmarking tests comparing their database to several others. The evaluation used a dataset of 99 million rows and executed queries typical of ad-hoc analytics and real-time dashboards to assess each database's performance boundaries. As you can see, ClickHouse excelled in most of the queries used compared to other databases. For a comprehensive view of the benchmark results, you can refer to the full report at the [provided link](https://github.com/ClickHouse/ClickBench/?tab=readme-ov-file).

## AWS Lambda Scaling & Concurrency

We assessed the concurrency and scale limitations of a single AWS Lambda to ensure this could serve our needs. As a reminder, our Lambda connector will be mapped to a number of Kinesis shards (AWS’s version of a stream topic). There is no cap on the number of event source mappings (triggers) that can be set for a single Lambda function.

Regarding the max potential data flow that might be sent to our Lambda, a Kinesis shard can write up to 1,000 records per second.

Regarding Lambda concurrency limitations, each function can scale up to 1,000 additional execution environments every 10 seconds.

As our Lambda processes each record in milliseconds, we expect these limits to adequately cover most user needs.
